Yes, there are much better ways. The right approach depends on your security requirement — email attachments are actually the worst choice for confidentiality since you lose control once sent.

Recommended: DocSend (industry standard for investors)

Instead of attaching PDFs, upload each one to DocSend and send each investor a unique, access-controlled link. Benefits:
•  Each link works only for that recipient (you set it)
•  You can revoke access anytime
•  You see exactly who opened it, for how long, page by page
•  Used widely in VC/deal flow — investors expect it

Pair it with Mailmeteor (Gmail add-on) or Lemlist for the bulk sending with mail merge.



If you must send actual PDF attachments

Python script is the most flexible:

import smtplib
from email.mime.multipart import MIMEMultipart
from email.mime.base import MIMEBase
from email.mime.text import MIMEText
from email import encoders
import pandas as pd

df = pd.read_csv("investors.csv")  # columns: email, name, pdf_path

for _, row in df.iterrows():
    msg = MIMEMultipart()
    msg["To"] = row["email"]
    msg["Subject"] = f"Deal memo - {row['name']}"
    
    with open(row["pdf_path"], "rb") as f:
        part = MIMEBase("application", "octet-stream")
        part.set_payload(f.read())
        encoders.encode_base64(part)
        part.add_header("Content-Disposition", f"attachment; filename={row['name']}.pdf")
        msg.attach(part)
    
    # Send via SendGrid/SMTP

Use SendGrid's API instead of raw SMTP for reliability at 100 recipients.

